<Subpage
  title="You can love someone and miss them at the same time."
  lead="It's a strange kind of ache, because nothing is obviously wrong. They're right there. Sometimes it's a marriage that runs fine on the surface while the closeness has quietly thinned out. Sometimes it's a grown child you used to talk to easily, and now every conversation feels a little careful."
  metaTitle="The Distance Between You — Ennea Evolution"
  metaDescription="They're still right here. Somehow they're still out of reach. Working on your side of the distance with someone you love."
  start="You don't need the other person to be willing. You don't even need them to know you're doing this. Bring the relationship as it is, the distance, the carefulness, the conversation you keep not having. We'll start with the only part of it that has ever really been yours to work with: your side."
>
  <p>Sometimes it's the same disagreement in different clothes, and you're tired in a way sleep doesn't fix.</p>
  <p><strong>Underneath all of it is the same quiet thing: you miss someone who hasn't gone anywhere.</strong></p>
  <p>This work is about your side of that distance. Not because it's your fault, and not because you're the only one in it, but because your side is the only side you can actually do anything about. That turns out to be more than enough to change things.</p>

  <h3>You might recognize this</h3>
  <ul class="ticklist">
    <li>You miss someone who is sitting six feet away from you.</li>
    <li>Your conversations have gotten careful, and you're not sure when that started.</li>
    <li>You know their schedule and their moods better than you know what they're actually thinking.</li>
    <li>When you do try to talk about the hard thing, it tends to go somewhere neither of you meant it to go.</li>
    <li>You catch yourself editing what you say around them, smoothing it, softening it, holding part of it back.</li>
    <li>Some days you feel like two people who know everything about each other and somehow can't reach each other.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>It usually isn't what you think it is</h3>
  <p>Most people assume distance means something dramatic happened. Often it didn't, and that's what makes it so confusing. The person is still there. The routines are still there. What went missing is the feeling that you're still finding each other. It rarely arrives in a single moment. Life gets busy, the relationship starts running on its routines, and slowly you stop responding to the person in front of you and start responding to your idea of them.</p>
  <p>And here's the part worth holding onto: a lot of what hurts in a close relationship isn't what you think is happening. When two people who love each other keep missing each other, it's rarely because one of them is doing it wrong. It's usually two people each protecting something, in ways that happen to set the other one off, neither of them choosing it on purpose. <strong>So much of the hurt turns out to be misread.</strong> And reaching this particular person, with their own way of loving and withdrawing and hearing things, is something that can be learned.</p>

  <h3>Working on your side of it</h3>
  <p>The other person doesn't have to come for this to help. That isn't a workaround; it's how this kind of work actually works. When one person in a relationship genuinely shifts, the relationship can't stay where it was. It has to reorganize around the change.</p>
  <p>We start by understanding the other person more clearly, sometimes for the first time in years. Not the version you've been carrying, the real one. How they tend to operate, what their behavior actually means underneath, what they might be reacting to when they go quiet or get sharp. When the other person starts to make more sense, the distance does too, and a good deal of what you've been taking personally turns out not to have been about you at all.</p>
  <p>Then we look at your part of it, gently. Not to assign blame, but because your part is where your power is. What happens in you when you feel unheard, what you're protecting in those moments, what tends to happen right before the connection breaks down. From there, you can try something different: saying the true thing in a way this person can actually take in, staying steady instead of going careful, meeting who they are now instead of who they were when you stopped looking closely.</p>

  <h3>What changes</h3>
  <p>You stop feeling so alone with someone you love. That's the first thing most people notice. The carefulness eases. Conversations stop feeling like something you have to manage, because you're talking to a person again instead of a version of them. Hard conversations land closer to where you meant them to. And the distance stops feeling like a permanent fact about the relationship and starts looking like what it usually was: two people who lost the thread for a while and are finding it again.</p>
  <p>Often the person you love responds, even though they never sat in a single session, because you've changed what you bring into the room between you. You stop missing someone who's sitting right next to you. They were there the whole time. You were both just a little out of reach, and now you're not.</p>
